ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[There are not enough clinical signs or tests to know what is really
happening. However, contagious caprine pleuropneumonia (CCPP) is a
_Mycoplasma _ biotype F38, which causes a highly contagious, lethal
disease in goats. It appears to be transmitted by infective aerosol.
Morbidity can be 100 percent and mortality 60 to 100 percent. CCPP
presents with a cough, weakness, anorexic and a nasal discharge
accompanied by an elevation in temperature.
It will be interesting to know what is happening as this could still be a
new or related biotype. - Mod.TG]
